# Dual Servo Motor Control with Arduino

This Arduino project demonstrates how to control **two servo motors** using the `Servo.h` library. The servos are connected to digital pins 8 and 9 of the Arduino and sweep between 0Â°, 90Â°, and 180Â° repeatedly with a 1-second delay between each position.

## ðŸ§° Hardware Required

- 1 x Arduino Uno (or compatible board)
- 2 x Servo motors (SG90 or similar)
- Jumper wires
- Breadboard (optional)
- External 5V power supply (recommended for multiple servos)

## ðŸ”Œ Circuit Diagram

| Servo     | Signal Pin (orenge) | VCC(red)   | GND (brown)  |
|-----------|-------------|--------|--------|
| Servo 1   | D9          | 5V     | GND    |
| Servo 2   | D8          | 5V     | GND    |

> **Note:** Use a common ground between the Arduino and the external power supply if you use one.

## ðŸ“„ Code Explanation

The code uses the `Servo` library to control the angle of two servos. It moves both servos to 0Â°, then 90Â°, then 180Â°, pausing for 1 second between each position.

### Arduino Code

```cpp
#include <Servo.h> // Include the Servo library

Servo servo1; // Servo on pin 9
Servo servo2; // Servo on pin 8

void setup() {
  servo1.attach(9); // Attach servo1 to pin 9
  servo2.attach(8); // Attach servo2 to pin 8
}

void loop() {
  servo1.write(0);
  servo2.write(0);
  delay(1000);

  servo1.write(90);
  servo2.write(90);
  delay(1000);

  servo1.write(180);
  servo2.write(180);
  delay(1000);
}
